-- ============================================================================
-- Follow-up call script v2 + coach profile prompts (Hugo 2026-05-08)
--
-- Hugo-approved one-call close script. Every road leads to sending the
-- proposal. Follow up next day. AI coach prompts matched to script stages.
-- ============================================================================

-- ─── Part A: update the follow-up call script body ─────────────────

UPDATE wk_call_scripts
SET name = 'NFSTAY follow-up call script',
    body_md = E'## NFSTAY FOLLOW-UP CALL SCRIPT\n\n*Goal: Check interest → pitch → get a decision → send the proposal either way. Follow up next day.*\n\n---\n\n### STAGE 1 — OPEN\n\n> "Hey {{first_name}}, it''s {{agent_first_name}} from NFSTAY. We spoke the other day — I sent you the breakdown about the joint venture partnership for the 15-bed property in Liverpool. Minimum £500 to get involved. Do you recall? Did you get a chance to look at it?"\n\n- **Yes:** "Nice — what did you think?" *(go to Stage 2)*\n- **No:** "No worries. Want me to run you through it quickly now? It''ll take two minutes." *(go to Stage 3)*\n- **Didn''t receive:** "That happens. Let me walk you through the key points now and I''ll resend it after." *(go to Stage 3)*\n\n---\n\n### STAGE 2 — GAUGE\n\n> "So based on what you saw — is that something you''d want to move forward with? Like, joint venture with us on the property?"\n\n- **Yes / interested:** "Great — let me tell you a bit more about how it works." *(go to Stage 3)*\n- **Maybe / unsure:** "What''s holding you back? Let me fill in the gaps." *(go to Stage 3)*\n- **Questions:** Answer from KB, then *(go to Stage 3)*\n\n---\n\n### STAGE 3 — THE PITCH\n\n> "So here''s what we''re doing. We''ve got just under 100 properties across Manchester and Liverpool. The one I sent you is a 15-bed in Liverpool — it''s already live on Airbnb, already generating income."\n\n> "The revenue on this property is between 9 and 10 percent monthly return. So in about a year, you''ve made your money back. And you''ve still got four years of pure profit after that on a 5-year agreement."\n\n> "And it''s not like you''re just putting money in and hoping for the best. This is a joint venture — you''re an actual partner. You vote on decisions, you see the live bookings, you see the income, everything''s transparent on the platform."\n\n> "You can start with just £500 to test the waters. See how it works, see the returns coming in, and then decide if you want to get more involved."\n\n> "What do you think?"\n\n---\n\n### STAGE 4 — THE DECISION\n\n> "So {{first_name}} — is this something you''d want to move forward with?"\n\n**Pause. Wait for their reply. Do not fill the silence.**\n\n- **Yes:** "Brilliant. What I''ll do is send you the full proposal — it lays out everything: the property, the returns, how the partnership works, your rights. Have a read through and I''ll call you tomorrow to go through any questions. What''s your best email?"\n- **Maybe / need to think:** "That''s fair. Look, let me send you the proposal anyway — it''s got everything laid out properly so you can make a decision with all the facts in front of you. No commitment, just read through it. I''ll call you tomorrow to see what you think."\n- **Need to speak to someone:** "Makes sense. I''ll send the proposal to you now — you can go through it together. I''ll follow up tomorrow."\n- **Not right now:** "No problem. I''ll send you the proposal anyway so you''ve got it when the time''s right. It costs nothing to have a look."\n- **Hard no, not interested at all:** "Fair enough, I respect that. If anything changes you''ve got my number. All the best."\n\n*Unless it''s a hard no → send the proposal.*\n\n---\n\n### STAGE 5 — SEND & LOCK NEXT-DAY FOLLOW-UP\n\n> "I''ll get that proposal over to you today. I''ll give you a call tomorrow — does morning or afternoon work better?"\n\nConfirm the time. Then:\n\n> "Perfect. Have a read through before then and jot down any questions. Speak to you tomorrow, {{first_name}}."\n\n---\n\n### OBJECTION HANDLING (answer → loop back to Stage 4)\n\n| They say | You say |\n|---|---|\n| "I need to think about it" | "Of course. What specifically are you weighing up? I might be able to clear it up now." *(answer, then:)* "Let me send you the proposal so you''ve got everything to think about properly." |\n| "Sounds risky" | "Any property deal has risk. But here you can see the live performance, you vote on every decision, and the agreements are all legally drafted. Have a read of the proposal — it''s all in there." |\n| "Is this regulated?" | "It''s a joint venture — you''re an active partner with real decision-making power. You vote on strategy, rates, even the management company. That''s why it sits outside the FCA. It''s all laid out in the proposal." |\n| "I''ve been burned before" | "I hear you. That''s why we''re fully transparent — live bookings, live income, you see everything. Read the proposal and judge for yourself." |\n| "£500 seems too good to be true" | "That''s the starting point to test the waters. The returns depend on actual bookings, not promises. You can see it all on the platform." |\n| "Call me back another time" | "Tell you what — let me just send the proposal now so you''ve got it. Read it when you''ve got five minutes, and I''ll call you tomorrow. That way it''s on your terms." |'
WHERE name ILIKE '%follow%up%';

-- ─── Part B: update the Follow-up coach profile prompts ────────────

UPDATE wk_coach_profiles
SET coach_style_prompt = E'You are a live AI call coach for NFSTAY. This is a FOLLOW-UP call — the lead has already been contacted and received a deal breakdown.\n\nTone: natural, conversational, confident. Not salesy or cheesy. The lead knows who we are.\n\nRules:\n- UK English only. No American spelling or phrasing.\n- One short actionable coaching card at a time.\n- Never use acting notes, stage directions, or multiple response variants.\n- Be direct — this is a closing call. Every stage leads to sending the proposal.\n- If the lead raises FCA/regulatory concerns, use the JV defence framing from the knowledge base.\n- Coach the agent to PAUSE and WAIT after asking the decision question. Do not fill silence.',
    coach_script_prompt = E'CALL TYPE: FOLLOW-UP (one-call close)\n\nGOAL: Get a decision on whether they want to move forward. Send the proposal EITHER WAY (unless hard refusal). Lock a next-day follow-up.\n\nSTAGES:\n1. OPEN — Remind them: "We spoke about the JV partnership for the 15-bed in Liverpool, minimum £500." Ask if they saw the breakdown. Every answer leads to the next stage.\n2. GAUGE — If they saw it: "Is that something you''d want to move forward with? Joint venture with us?" If not: walk them through the pitch.\n3. THE PITCH — Key numbers: ~100 properties across Manchester/Liverpool. 15-bed Liverpool, live on Airbnb. 9-10% monthly return. Money back in ~1 year, 4 years pure profit. JV = active partner, you vote on everything. Start with £500 to test the waters.\n4. THE DECISION — "So {{first_name}}, is this something you''d want to move forward with?" PAUSE. WAIT. Do not fill the silence. Whatever they say (except hard no) → send the proposal.\n5. SEND & LOCK — Send proposal today. Follow up TOMORROW, not "in a few days". Confirm morning or afternoon.\n\nOBJECTION RULE: Every objection loops back to sending the proposal. "Let me send you the proposal so you''ve got everything to think about properly."\n\nCONFIDENCE RULE: Answer confidently from general property/business knowledge if the KB doesn''t have the exact fact. Never say "I don''t know" — say "From what I understand..." and give your best answer.\n\nCRITICAL: The ONLY exit without sending the proposal is a hard refusal to do business entirely. Everything else → proposal goes out.'
WHERE name = 'Follow-up';
